 <title>We’re Throwing a HackFest and Everyone Is Invited</title>
 <link>https://identity.allseenalliance.org/news-and-events/blogs/2014/04/we-re-throwing-hackfest-and-everyone-invited</link>
 <description>
		&lt;span class=&quot;a2a_kit a2a_target addtoany_list&quot; id=&quot;da2a_3&quot;&gt;
			&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_facebook&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_twitter&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_google_plus&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_dd addtoany_share_save&quot; href=&quot;http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=https%3A%2F%2Fidentity.allseenalliance.org%2Fnews-and-events%2Fblogs%2F2014%2F04%2Fwe-re-throwing-hackfest-and-everyone-invited&amp;amp;title=Blogs%20-%20AllSeen%20Alliance&quot;&gt; Share&lt;/a&gt;
		&lt;/span&gt;
		
		
  &lt;div class=&quot;field-body view-mode-rss&quot;&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;The Internet of Everything is about making smart connected devices and objects work together. The motivation for the AllSeen Alliance and the reason for the AllJoyn framework is to enable developers from multiple industries, using various programming languages, tools chains, operating environments and hardware platforms to create applications designed for interoperability. But to make this a reality we need to provide developers with the information and tools they need to get started developing IoE applications.  This is the goal of the first &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.allseenalliance.org/develop/hackfests/1may2014hackfest#registration&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;AllSeen Alliance HackFest&lt;/a&gt;, to be held May 1 in San Jose; an intensive day of training labs and hands-on coding, and a lot of fun!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Internet of Everything continues to gain steam as one of technology’s hottest topics and market opportunities; Gartner recently predicted the IoE will encompass 26 billion devices by 2020, up from 900 million five years ago; so needless to say we are expecting a lot of interest in the HackFest.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This HackFest is the first public event since the AllSeen Alliance formed in December last year. It will be co-located with the Linux Foundation&#039;s Embedded Linux Conference at the San Jose Marriott, is free to attend and open to anyone. You do not need to be an AllSeen Alliance member or have any previous connection to the group, just bring your notebook computer, coding skills and desire to work in small teams on a cool IoE project.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;At the HackFest you will learn more about how the AllJoyn framework enables devices to discover each other, connect and interact and how to develop interoperable applications. It is also an opportunity to talk to others in the technical community and swap ideas, give your opinion, and, of course, write code. There’s even a free lunch.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;HackFests are a key component of the AllSeen Alliance&#039;s mission to grow the code, expand the community and enable the widespread use of the AllJoyn framework. As with all open, collaborative initiatives, it is literally in developers’ hands to move the project forward. So we’re really excited about the event.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are only a limited number of seats available, so if you’re interested in attending, reserve your seat today. To view the full agenda or register, visit the &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.allseenalliance.org/develop/hackfests/1may2014hackfest#registration&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;HackFest Wiki&lt;/a&gt;.  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We hope to see you on May 1!&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;
</description>
 <pubDate>Wed, 16 Apr 2014 15:08:09 +0000</pubDate>
