<item>
 <title>An Open-Source Framework for the Internet of Everything Gets an Update</title>
 <link>https://identity.allseenalliance.org/news-and-events/blogs/2014/03/open-source-framework-internet-everything-gets-update</link>
 <description>
		&lt;span class=&quot;a2a_kit a2a_target addtoany_list&quot; id=&quot;da2a_4&quot;&gt;
			&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_facebook&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_twitter&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_button_google_plus&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;a2a_dd addtoany_share_save&quot; href=&quot;http://www.addtoany.com/share_save#url=https%3A%2F%2Fidentity.allseenalliance.org%2Fnews-and-events%2Fblogs%2F2014%2F03%2Fopen-source-framework-internet-everything-gets-update&amp;amp;title=Blogs%20-%20AllSeen%20Alliance&quot;&gt; Share&lt;/a&gt;
		&lt;/span&gt;
		
		
  &lt;div class=&quot;field-body view-mode-rss&quot;&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Once in a while, I bump into someone still uncertain about the difference between “AllSeen” and “AllJoyn.” So let me start with a quick refresher: The AllSeen Alliance is the consortium of companies, 35 as of today, that are collaborating on an open source software framework that allows devices and systems to autonomously discover and interact with nearby products regardless of brand, transport layer, platform or operating system. AllJoyn is the framework codebase.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Today, the Alliance is announcing the first new release of AllJoyn since the Alliance’s creation. &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.allseenalliance.org/release/overview&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Version 14.02&lt;/a&gt; contains performance and stability improvements and bug fixes, among other improvements to advance this universal, collaborative framework for the Internet of Everything.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Version 14.02’s release originally was going to be in April, but we moved it up to align with a four-month release cadence. So you can expect additional releases in June and October. If you’re wondering about the version number 14.02, the next one with be 14.06, the one after 14.10. Get it?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In parallel to developing the new release, we have been running a &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.allseenalliance.org/training&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;series of training sessions&lt;/a&gt; to help bring the community up to speed on the AllJoyn framework and base-services. These presentations have been recorded and are available for download on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://wiki.allseenalliance.org/training&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;AllSeen Wiki&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;With 14.02 released earlier than expected, we now have more time for feature development on 14.06. The exact feature sets for core and base services are still being nailed down but will be presented by the Alliance working group chairs to the technical steering committee for approval within the next several weeks.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Speaking of &lt;a href=&quot;https://allseenalliance.org/about-allseen/governance/project-and-working-group-lifecycle&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;working groups&lt;/a&gt;, we currently have three -- core, base services and development tools, essentially grandfathered in from alljoyn.org. We have a proposal for a working group on Certification &amp;amp; Compliance (C&amp;amp;C). Since interoperability in the Internet of Things is the driving force behind the AllSeen Alliance, getting the C&amp;amp;C working group up and running to develop test cases, frameworks and test code is an especially high priority for the Alliance.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you have an idea for a working group or a project within one of the existing working groups and are willing either individually or as a corporation to commit the development resources to make it happen, there is a simple process for getting a proposal in front of the Alliance’s Technical Services Committee. &lt;a href=&quot;https://allseenalliance.org/about-allseen/governance/project-and-working-group-lifecycle&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Learn more about submitting a proposal.&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Greg Burns is the AllSeen Alliance TSC Chair&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;
</description>
 <pubDate>Mon, 03 Mar 2014 16:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
